The main function of any PFD, of course, is to keep a person afloat, or buoyant-even with heavy clothes and gear. Its buoyancy also helps a stranded person save energy, because without a PFD a swimmer has to continually work to stay afloat. Some designs also help keep a victim\'92s face out of the water. A PFD\'92s buoyancy is the amount of weight it can keep afloat. High buoyancy is over 20 pounds. This may sound low, but water provides lift, so the average adult needs only 7 to 12 pounds of buoyancy.\
\
A PFD can only save your life if it is available when you need it, and you wear it properly. Be sure you know where you keep your own life preserver and also where the spare PFD\'92s are stowed in the engine room. Use the opportunity at weekly boat drills to practice donning your life jacket, and inspect it frequently for tears and open seams; for lost buoyant material; for waterlogged, oil-soaked, or hardened buoyant material; and for proper functioning of the light and whistle.\
\
**Type I life preserver.** This it the type of life preserver which is used by all hands aboard merchant ships. Every cadet is given instruction in its use during *STCW Basic Safety Training* during orientation.\
\
The Type I life preserver is an international orange colored vest filled with a sufficient amount of inherently buoyant material to give it 22 pounds of buoyancy, and fitted with straps to hold it in position on the wearer. The PFD is equipped with a whistle for attracting attention, and reflective tape and a light to make it more visible at night. Because of its high buoyancy, it is bulky and not normally worn continuously while working.\
\
**Type V PFD Work Vest.** This is a \'93one size fits all\'94 work vest which provides basic flotation for workers who fall in the water. It is intended for people working in exposed locations over the water or near the edge of the deck, and also for deck crews on tugs and barges. It is assumed that rescue will occur quickly. A work vest is only approved for use consistent with its design.\
\
The main advantage of a work vest is that is has relatively little bulk and does not significantly restrict the wearers movement, making it suitable for continuous wear. It is less buoyant than a Type I PFD and will not hold an unconscious wearer\'92s face clear of the water. Because it has less buoyancy a conscious wearer\'92s face may also be covered by waves in rough water.\
\
**Immersion Suit.** Immersion suits, also known as survival suits or \'93gumby suits,\'94 are a full body, insulated flotation device which can protect you from hypothermia and prevent you from drowning. Because hypothermia is a major factor in lives lost at sea, the U.S. Coast Guard now requires immersion suits on all documented vessels operating north of 32 degrees N and seaward of the Coastal Boundary Line.\
\
